# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: glutamine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was first reported by Henri Victor Regnault in 1840.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Industrially, it is usually produced in a two-step process from vinyl chloride.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction is catalyzed by a variety of Lewis acids, mainly aluminium chloride, iron(III) chloride, or zinc chloride.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction proceeds at 80%–90% yield, and the hydrogen chloride byproduct can be recycled to the first step in the process.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The major side-product is the related compound 1,1,2-trichloroethane, from which the 1,1,1-trichloroethane can be separated by distillation.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is sold with stabilizers because it is unstable with respect to dehydrochlorination and attacks some metals.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Stabilizers comprise up to 8% of the formulation, including acid scavengers (epoxides, amines) and complexants.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] One discontinued product contained only 1,4-dioxane (2%±1%), while another chemical supplier included 2.5% 1,4-dioxane, 0.47% 1,2-butylene oxide, and 0.35% nitromethane as stabilizers.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is an excellent solvent for many organic compounds and one of the least toxic of the chlorinated hydrocarbons.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is generally considered non-polar, but owing to the good polarizability of the chlorine atoms, it is a superior solvent for organic compounds that do not dissolve well in hydrocarbons such as hexane.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Prior to the Montreal Protocol, it was widely used for cleaning metal parts and circuit boards, as a photoresist solvent in the electronics industry, as an aerosol propellant, as a cutting fluid additive, and as a solvent for inks, paints, adhesives, and other coatings.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used to dry-clean leather and suede.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Use in dry-cleaning remained until the 1980s.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used as an insecticidal fumigant.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also the standard cleaner for photographic film.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Other commonly available solvents damage emulsion and base (acetone will dissolve triacetate base on most films), and thus are not suitable for this application.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The standard replacement, Forane 141 is much less effective, and tends to leave a residue.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also used as a thinner in correction fluid products such as liquid paper.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Many of its applications previously used carbon tetrachloride (which was banned in US consumer products in 1970).
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In turn, 1,1,1-trichloroethane itself is now being replaced by other solvents in the laboratory.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Phase-out of 1,1,1-Trichloroethane due to ozone depletion lead to a resurgence of the use of trichloroethylene in metal degreasing.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Methyl chloroform was also used as a veterinary anthelmintic.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was one of the volatile organochlorides that have been tried as alternatives to chloroform in anaesthesia.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In the 1880s, it was found to be a safe and strong substitute for chloroform but its production was too expensive and difficult for the era.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In 1880, 1,1,1-trichloroethane was suggested as an anaesthetic.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was first referred to as methyl-chloroform in the same year.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] At the time, the narcotic effects of chloral hydrate were owed to a hypothetical metabolic pathway to chloroform in "alkaline blood".
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Trichloroethane was studied for its structural similarity to chloral and potential anaesthetic effects.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] However, trichloroethane did not exhibit any conversion to chloroform in laboratory experiments.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The 1,1,2-Trichloroethane (vinyl trichloride) isomer, which lacked a trichloromethyl group, exhibited anaesthetic effects even stronger than the 1,1,1 isomer.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The International Agency for Research on Cancer places 1,1,1-trichloroethane in Group 2A as a probable carcinogen.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is a fairly potent greenhouse gas with a 100-year global warming potential of 169 relative to carbon dioxide.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This is nonetheless less than a tenth that of carbon tetrachloride — which it replaced as a solvent — due to its relatively short atmospheric lifetime of about 5 years.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The Montreal Protocol targeted 1,1,1-trichloroethane as a compound responsible for ozone depletion and banned its use beginning in 1996.
[src:glutamine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Since then, its manufacture and use have been phased out throughout most of the world, and its atmospheric concentration has declined substantially.
[src:glutamine/1-3-diaminopropane] The potassium salt was used in the alkyne zipper reaction.
[src:glutamine/1-3-diaminopropane] Known uses of 1,3-diaminopropane are in the synthesis of piroxantrone and losoxantrone.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] In one industrial chemical synthesis, acetylene reacts with two equivalents of formaldehyde to form butyne-1,4-diol.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Hydrogenation of butyne-1,4-diol gives butane-1,4-diol.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] It is also made on an industrial scale from maleic anhydride in the Davy process, which is first converted to the methyl maleate ester, then hydrogenated.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Other routes are from butadiene, allyl acetate and succinic acid.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] A biological route to BD has been commercialized that uses a genetically modified organism.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] The biosynthesis proceeds via 4-hydroxybutyrate.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is used industrially as a solvent and in the manufacture of some types of plastics, elastic fibers and polyurethanes.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] In organic chemistry, 1,4-butanediol is used for the synthesis of γ-butyrolactone (GBL).
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] In the presence of phosphoric acid and high temperature, it dehydrates to the important solvent tetrahydrofuran.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] At about 200 °C in the presence of soluble ruthenium catalysts, the diol undergoes dehydrogenation to form butyrolactone.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] It is used to synthesize 1,4-butanediol diglycidyl ether which is then used as a reactive diluent for epoxy resins.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-Butanediol is used in the production of polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) plastic.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] World production of butane-1,4-diol was claimed to be about one million metric tons per year and market price is about US$2,000 (€1,600) per ton in 2005.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] In 2013, worldwide production was claimed to be billions of pounds (consistent with approximately one million metric tons).
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Almost half of it is dehydrated to tetrahydrofuran to make fibers such as Spandex.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is also used as a recreational drug known by some users as "Bute", "One Comma Four", "Liquid Fantasy", "One Four Bee" or "One Four B-D-O".
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Some federal courts in the United States have stated that 1,4-butanediol exerts effects similar to its metabolite, GABA analogue gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB), but several other federal courts have ruled that it does not.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-but***e***nediol (CAS 110-64-5) may be incorrectly sold as 1,4-butanediol but should not be confused with it.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is rapidly converted into GHB acid by the enzymes alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase, and differing levels of these enzymes may account for differences in effects and side effects between users.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] While co-administration of ethanol and GHB already poses serious risks, co-administration of ethanol with 1,4-butanediol will interact considerably and has many other potential risks.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] This is because the same enzymes that are responsible for metabolizing alcohol also metabolize 1,4-butanediol so there is a strong chance of a dangerous drug interaction.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol seems to have two types of pharmacological actions.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] The major psychoactive effects of 1,4-butanediol are because it is metabolized into GHB; however there is a study suggesting that 1,4-butanediol may have potential alcohol-like pharmacological effects on its own.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] The study arrived at this conclusion based on the finding that butane-1,4-diol coadministered with ethanol led to potentiation of some of the behavioral effects of ethanol.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] However, potentiation of ethanol's effects may simply be caused by competition for the alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes with co-administered 1,4-butanediol.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] The shared metabolic rate-limiting steps thus leads to slowed metabolism and clearance for both compounds including ethanol's known toxic metabolite acetaldehyde.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Another study found no effect following intracerebroventricular injection of butane-1,4-diol in rats.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] This contradicts the hypothesis of butane-1,4-diol having inherent alcohol-like pharmacological effects.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Like gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, butane-1,4-diol is safe only in small amounts.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Adverse effects in higher doses include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, sedation, vertigo, and potentially death if ingested in large amounts.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Anxiolytic effects are diminished and side effects increased when used in combination with alcohol.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] While butane-1,4-diol is not currently scheduled federally in the United States, a number of states have classified 1,4-butanediol as a controlled substance.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Individuals have been prosecuted for possession of 1,4-butanediol under the Federal Analog Act as substantially similar to GHB.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] A federal case in New York in 2002 ruled that 1,4-butanediol could not be considered an analog of GHB under federal law, but that decision was later overturned by the Second Circuit.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] A jury in Federal District Court in Chicago found that 1,4-butanediol was not an analog of GHB under federal law, which was not disputed on the case's appeal to the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals, however this finding did not affect the outcome of the case.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] In the United Kingdom, 1,4-butanediol was scheduled in December 2009 (along with another GHB precursor, gamma-butyrolactone) as a Class C controlled substance.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] In Germany, the drug is not explicitly illegal, but might also be treated as illegal if used as a drug.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] It is controlled as a Schedule VI precursor in Canada.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] A toy called "Bindeez" ("Aqua Dots" in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 because of the presence of butane-1,4-diol.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other by sprinkling water.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] The production plant seems to have intended to cut costs by replacing less toxic pentane-1,5-diol with butane-1,4-diol.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] ChemNet China listed the price of butane-1,4-diol at between about US$1,350–2,800 per metric ton, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700 per metric ton.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] In August 2021, several people fell severely ill after consuming drinks at building L2.01 at the Lichtwiese Campus of Darmstadt Technical University, Germany.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Seven showed severe symptoms, two were transported to a hospital in Frankfurt am Main, and a 30-year-old person was, for a time, in a critical state.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol had been detected in milk packages, as well as in water filters.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] At the location, detectives also found bromophenols and dicyclohexylamine.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] A variety of 1,4-butanediol derivatives are GHB-like drugs or GHB receptor agonists.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] These include GHB itself, γ-butyrolactone (GBL), aceburic acid, ethyl acetoxy butanoate (EAB), Γ-crotonolactone, γ-hydroxybutyraldehyde, γ-hydroxyvaleric acid (GHV), γ-valerolactone (GVL), γ-hydroxycrotonic acid (GHC or T-HCA), and 4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid (UMB68), among others.
[src:glutamine/1-4-butanediol] An analogue that is not a 1,4-butanediol derivative but is related and still shows affinity for the GHB receptor is 3-chloropropanoic acid (UMB66).
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC is the precursor to the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] It is synthesized by the enzyme ACC synthase (EC 4.4.1.14) from methionine and converted to ethylene by ACC oxidase (EC 1.14.17.4).
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC also exhibits ethylene-independent signaling that plays a critical role in pollination and seed production by activating proteins similar to those involved in nervous system responses in humans and animals.
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] More specifically, ACC signaling promotes secretion of the pollen tube chemoattractant LURE1.2 in ovular sporophytic tissue thus enhancing pollen tube attraction.
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] Additionally, ACC activates Ca2+-containing ion currents via glutamate receptor-like (GLR) channels in root protoplasts.
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC can be used by soil microorganisms (both bacteria and fungi) as a source of nitrogen and carbon.
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] As such, using ACC to incubate soils has been proven to induce the gene abundance encoding ACC-deaminases, which may have positive consequences on plant growth and stress tolerance.
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] ACC is also an exogenous partial agonist of the mammalian NMDA receptor.
[src:glutamine/1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic-acid] In 2019, the United States Environmental Protection Agency issued notice of an application for an experimental use permit to be issued for use of ACC as a pesticide.
[src:glutamine/11-ketoprogesterone] 11-Ketoprogesterone is reportedly devoid of androgenic, estrogenic, and progestogenic activity.
[src:glutamine/11-ketoprogesterone] 11β-Hydroxyprogesterone has also been reported to be devoid of progestogenic activity, but has subsequently been reported to possess about 1% of the progestogenic activity of progesterone.
[src:glutamine/11-ketoprogesterone] A halogenated derivative of 11-ketoprogesterone, 9α-bromo-11-ketoprogesterone, possesses relatively high progestogenic activity.
[src:glutamine/11-ketoprogesterone] Similarly to 11α-hydroxyprogesterone and 11β-hydroxyprogesterone, 11-ketoprogesterone is reported to act as an inhibitor of the enzyme 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase.
[src:glutamine/11-ketoprogesterone] It has also been found to act as a weak negative allosteric modulator of the GABAA receptor.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Diberal, unlike most barbiturates, can have convulsant actions.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] This is uncommon, as barbiturates typically enhance the function of GABA as allorestic modulators and agonists (at higher doses), therefore having anticonvulsant properties.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Depending on which isomer is used, it can have either convulsant or anticonvulsant actions.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] The different pharmacological profile between isomers is thought to be due to the differences in the formation of hydrogen bonds at the binding sites.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (+)-DMBB is the atypical enantiomer of diberal.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It is atypical in the means that it has convulsant action, unlike most barbiturate drugs.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] Unlike (+)-DMBB, the (−)-isomer is similar to most barbiturates by having anticonvulsant action.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] It has been found that administration of (−)-DMBB reverses the convulsant actions of (+)-DMBB.
[src:glutamine/5-1-3-dimethylbutyl-5-ethylbarbituric-acid] (−)-DMBB is slightly more potent than pentobarbital in its depressant properties.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] In human blood, glutamine is the most abundant free amino acid.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The dietary sources of glutamine include especially the protein-rich foods like beef, chicken, fish, dairy products, eggs, vegetables like beans, beets, cabbage, spinach, carrots, parsley, vegetable juices and also in wheat, papaya, Brussels sprouts, celery, kale and fermented foods like miso.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The one-letter symbol Q for glutamine was assigned in alphabetical sequence to N for asparagine, being larger by merely one methylene –CH2– group.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Note that P was used for proline, and O was avoided due to similarity with D.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The mnemonic *Q*lutamine was also proposed.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine maintains redox balance by participating in glutathione synthesis and contributing to anabolic processes such as lipid synthesis by reductive carboxylation.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine provides a source of carbon and nitrogen for use in other metabolic processes.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine is present in serum at higher concentrations than other amino acids and is essential for many cellular functions.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Examples include the synthesis of nucleotides and non-essential amino acids.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] One of the most important functions of glutamine is its ability to be converted into α-KG, which helps to maintain the flow of the tricarboxylic acid cycle, generating ATP via the electron carriers NADH and FADH2.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The highest consumption of glutamine occurs in the cells of the intestines, kidney cells (where it is used for acid-base balance), activated immune cells, and many cancer cells.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine is produced industrially using mutants of *Brevibacterium flavum*, which gives ca.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] 40 g/L in 2 days using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine synthesis from glutamate and ammonia is catalyzed by the enzyme glutamine synthetase.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The majority of glutamine production occurs in muscle tissue, accounting for about 90% of all glutamine synthesized.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine is also released, in small amounts, by the lungs and brain.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Although the liver is capable of glutamine synthesis, its role in glutamine metabolism is more regulatory than productive, as the liver takes up glutamine derived from the gut via the hepatic portal system.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine is the most abundant naturally occurring, nonessential amino acid in the human body, and one of the few amino acids that can directly cross the blood–brain barrier.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Humans obtain glutamine through catabolism of proteins in foods they eat.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] In states where tissue is being built or repaired, like growth of babies, or healing from wounds or severe illness, glutamine becomes conditionally essential.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved L-glutamine oral powder, marketed as **Endari**, to reduce severe complications of sickle cell disease in people aged five years and older with the disorder.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The safety and efficacy of L-glutamine oral powder were studied in a randomized trial of subjects ages five to 58 years old with sickle cell disease who had two or more painful crises within the 12 months prior to enrollment in the trial.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Subjects were assigned randomly to treatment with L-glutamine oral powder or placebo, and the effect of treatment was evaluated over 48 weeks.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Subjects who received L-glutamine oral powder also had fewer occurrences of acute chest syndrome (a life-threatening complication of sickle cell disease) compared with patients who received a placebo (8.6 percent vs.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Common side effects of L-glutamine oral powder include constipation, nausea, headache, abdominal pain, cough, pain in the extremities, back pain and chest pain.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] L-glutamine oral powder received orphan drug designation.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The FDA granted the approval of Endari to Emmaus Medical Inc.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine is marketed as medical food and is prescribed when a medical professional believes a person in their care needs supplementary glutamine due to metabolic demands beyond what can be met by endogenous synthesis or diet.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine is safe in adults and in preterm infants.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Although glutamine is metabolized to glutamate and ammonia, both of which have neurological effects, their concentrations are not increased much, and no adverse neurological effects were detected.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] The observed safe level for supplemental L-glutamine in normal healthy adults is 14 g/day.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Adverse effects of glutamine have been described for people receiving home parenteral nutrition and those with liver-function abnormalities.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Although glutamine has no effect on the proliferation of tumor cells, it is still possible that glutamine supplementation may be detrimental in some cancer types.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Ceasing glutamine supplementation in people adapted to very high consumption may initiate a withdrawal effect, raising the risk of health problems such as infections or impaired integrity of the intestine.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine can exist in either of two enantiomeric forms, L-glutamine and D-glutamine.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine contains an α-amino group which is in the protonated −NH3+ form under biological conditions and a carboxylic acid group which is in the deprotonated −COO− form, known as carboxylate, under physiological conditions.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine supplementation was investigated for its possible effects in critically ill people or after abdominal surgery, but the low quality of research prevented conclusions about any effect.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Supplementation does not appear to have an effect in infants with significant stomach or intestinal disorders.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Clinical studies have investigated glutamine supplementation for supporting gut barrier function.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Glutamine has also been studied for the prevention and management of chemotherapy- or radiation-induced oral and gastrointestinal mucositis.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] Multiple randomized trials and meta-analyses suggest that glutamine supplementation may reduce the incidence or severity of high-grade oral mucositis, although findings are heterogeneous and not all studies demonstrate benefit.
[src:glutamine/glutamine] While commercial and lay sources describe plausible mechanisms by which glutamine may support intestinal barrier function, such claims should be interpreted in the context of available clinical evidence.
